## 8. Concurrency & Scalability

| Requirement | Design Decision |
|-------------|-----------------|
| 10 simultaneous frontend users | Flask dev server handles this. For production: Gunicorn with 4 sync workers (`gunicorn -w 4 app:app`) |
| In-memory state safety | All outreach logic is **stateless** (pure functions). No shared mutable state is read or written by these routes |
| No session handling needed | Both endpoints are read/compute only; no DB writes |
| AI call latency | P4: < 1 ms (local template). P5: ~1‚Äì3 s (Bedrock); acceptable for interactive use |

> **Deliberate scope limit:** The backend is designed for exactly 10 concurrent users. No queue, cache, or connection pooling is required.

---

## 9. AWS Deployment Notes (P5)

The single change needed to activate real AI in P5:

**File:** [backend/outreach.py](file:///c:/Users/dhyan/OneDrive/Desktop/linkedin-redesign/backend/outreach.py), function `_call_ai(prompt: str) -> str`

Replace the mock body with:

```python
import boto3, json

def _call_ai(prompt: str) -> str:
    client = boto3.client("bedrock-runtime", region_name="us-east-1")
    body = json.dumps({
        "inputText": prompt,
        "textGenerationConfig": {
            "maxTokenCount": 300,
            "temperature": 0.7,
            "topP": 0.9
        }
    })
    response = client.invoke_model(
        modelId="amazon.titan-text-express-v1",
        body=body,
        contentType="application/json",
        accept="application/json",
    )
    result = json.loads(response["body"].read())
    return result["results"][0]["outputText"]
```

All other code (routes, module interface, response schema) stays **identical**.

**IAM permission needed:**
```json
{ "Effect": "Allow", "Action": "bedrock:InvokeModel",
  "Resource": "arn:aws:bedrock:us-east-1::foundation-model/amazon.titan-text-express-v1" }
```

**Estimated cost:** ~$0.0008 per 1,000 output tokens (Titan Express). For 10 users √ó 10 messages/day = 100 calls/day ‚Üí negligible against $100‚Äì200 credit budget.

